Overview

Below is an analysis of the pilot study, with a total sample of N = 215, (female = 63, male = 152, non-binary = 0, prefer not to say = 0, Mage = 36.6, SD = 9.6).

Measures

We used two measures of moral perception. The first measure Moral Perception Scale (MPS) four items rated on 7-point Likert scales (with anchors Bad/Good, Immoral/Moral, Violent/Peaceful, Merciless/Empathetic), this showed excellent reliability = 0.84, M = 5.8, SD = 1. The second measure was a single item Moral Perception Measure (M1), participants were asked to Please Rate [character name] according to immoral or moral you view them on a slider rating from 0-100 with (0 = Very Immoral, and 100 = Very Moral); M = 77.3, SD = 16.

Differences in M1

## [1] A paired samples t-test revealed a significant difference in moral Perception between the Diagnostic Condition, (M = 79.35, SD = 13.64), and the Non-Diagnostic condition, (M =73.26, SD = 15.37), t(214) = 5.992, p = 0, d = 0.41.
